  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model — the gold standard of intrinsic valuation. No multiples, no comparables, no vibes. Just future cash flows discounted to today.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>Illinois Tool Works generated <strong>$2.71 billion</strong> in free cash flow in FY2025. This is operating cash flow minus capital expenditures. This is real cash the business produces after paying for everything.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We grow FCF at <strong>5% per year</strong> for 5 years. ITW is a mature, high-quality industrial compounder. Revenue growth is generally slow (low-single digits organically), but ITW excels at margin expansion and capital allocation, driving moderate FCF growth.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>2.5% forever</strong>. We use the <strong>Gordon Growth Model</strong>: Terminal Value = FCF₆ ÷ (discount rate − terminal growth rate). This aligns with long-term macroeconomic growth expectations for an industrial conglomerate.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>8.5%</strong> — our required rate of return. ITW is an established, diversified, highly profitable industrial with strong cash generation and lower beta, warranting a slightly lower cost of capital than high-growth tech.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Add net cash, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash (-$8.36B) = Equity Value. Divide by shares outstanding (288.2M) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>A DCF is only as good as its inputs. We're making exactly <strong>three</strong> judgment calls — everything else is math. Here's what we chose and why.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">5%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        ITW's top line grows slowly, roughly 1-3% organically. However, its decentralized operating model and 80/20 front-to-back philosophy consistently drive margin improvements. A 5% FCF growth rate strikes a balance between sluggish industrial end-markets and ITW's operational excellence.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">8.5%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        10Y Treasury is currently 4.18%. ITW is a Dividend Aristocrat with defensive characteristics and a strong balance sheet, yielding a lower beta. We demand an 8.5% return, applying a reasonable equity risk premium over the risk-free rate for a stable industrial blue-chip.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">2.5%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        An industrial conglomerate's long-term prospects are closely tied to global GDP and inflation. A 2.5% terminal growth rate assumes ITW maintains its competitive positioning and grows essentially in line with long-run global economic output.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FCF PROJECTIONS TABLE ═══ -->
  <h2>Projected Free Cash Flows</h2>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
          <th>FCF ($M)</th>
          <th>PV Factor</th>
          <th>Present Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Base (FY2025)</td>
          <td>${fcf2025.toLocaleString()}</td>
          <td>—</td>
          <td>—</td>
        </tr>
        {projectedFCF.map(p => (
          <tr>
