  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Aggressive share repurchases:</strong> ITW actively buys back shares. Fewer shares outstanding will naturally increase the per-share value over time, providing a tailwind.</li>
    <li><strong>Stronger macro environment:</strong> An industrial boom, reshoring trends, or extensive infrastructure spending could drive revenue growth above our baseline.</li>
    <li><strong>Further margin expansion:</strong> Continued execution of the enterprise strategy could lift operating margins closer to 30%, meaningfully boosting FCF.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Global industrial recession:</strong> As an industrial conglomerate, ITW is exposed to cyclical end-markets like automotive and construction. A prolonged recession would depress cash flows.</li>
    <li><strong>FX headwinds:</strong> With a significant global footprint, sustained dollar strength can erode reported earnings and cash flows.</li>
    <li><strong>Input cost inflation:</strong> Stubborn inflation in raw materials and labor could pressure margins if ITW cannot fully pass these costs to customers.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a DCF for an industrial stock?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While many value industrials on P/E or EV/EBITDA multiples across a cycle, a DCF captures the true cash generation power. It forces explicit assumptions about long-term growth and capital cost rather than relying on historical or peer-based multiples which may be distorted.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why an 8.5% discount rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The 10-year Treasury yields 4.18%. ITW is a highly stable, diversified Dividend Aristocrat with a strong balance sheet. This risk profile justifies a slightly lower equity risk premium compared to volatile tech stocks, landing us at an 8.5% hurdle rate.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is ITW's net cash negative?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">It is common for mature industrials to carry net debt. ITW utilizes debt optimally to lower its overall cost of capital and fund shareholder returns (dividends and buybacks). The debt level is very manageable given their robust free cash flow generation.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, and conviction in the assumptions.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

